<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="110" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,259,538]" pageId="9" pageNumber="110">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,367,393]" pageId="9" pageNumber="110">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Schmid-Egger &amp; Fallahzadeh &amp; Sadeghi, 2021" authorityName="Schmid-Egger &amp; Fallahzadeh &amp; Sadeghi" authorityYear="2021" box="[328,524,367,393]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Solierella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="110" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="persica" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[328,524,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="110">Solierella persica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[531,621,367,393]" pageId="9" pageNumber="110">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[531,621,367,393]" pageId="9" pageNumber="110" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is charaterized by a distinct shiny body surface, compared to the remaining species. This includes mesonotum, mespleuron, the episcrobal area, which is also nearly completely impunctate, and the interspaces of the propodeal enclosure. Punctation of vertex and mesosoma is sparser compared to remainnig species from 
<collectingCountry box="[348,396,476,502]" name="Iran" pageId="9" pageNumber="110">Iran</collectingCountry>
, apart from mesonotal punctation of 
<taxonomicName authority="Schmid-Egger &amp; Fallahzadeh &amp; Sadeghi, 2021" authorityName="Schmid-Egger &amp; Fallahzadeh &amp; Sadeghi" authorityYear="2021" box="[820,956,475,501]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Solierella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="110" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kermania" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[820,956,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="110">S. kermania</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[964,1056,475,501]" pageId="9" pageNumber="110">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[964,1056,475,501]" pageId="9" pageNumber="110" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, which is also more sparse. Legs including femora have large whitish parts, as the remaining new described species in this contribution.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
